[2] Texas
Date: Wed 19 Feb 2014
Source: Dallas (TX) News [edited]
http://www.dallasnews.com/news/metro/20140219-whooping-cough-cases-soared-in-dallas-county-last-year.ece?nclick_check=1


Any way you look at it, 2013 was a bad year for whooping cough. Dallas County counted the most cases of whooping cough, also called pertussis, in more than 2 decades with 404. Texas had to go back to the 1950s to find more cases than the 3908 confirmed last year [2013]. Its previous record was 5842 in 1959. But Tarrant County topped even that terrible distinction. Its 697 cases in 2013 beat the whooping cough record set there in 1940.

"It was an awful year," said Russell Jones, Tarrant County's chief epidemiologist. "We had the most pertussis cases of every county in Texas."
Other counties reported high numbers including Denton County with 312 and Collin with 203.

Jones blamed the spike on the cyclical nature of pertussis. The respiratory disease reappears annually with a noticeable increase in cases every 3 to 5 years. 5 years ago, Tarrant recorded 312 pertussis cases, Jones said. The county's previous record was set almost a decade before a vaccine became available for the disease.

To stem a repeat in 2014, local officials hope to encourage residents to update their immunizations against the disease.

[Byline: Sherry Jacobson]

