[5] Delaware (Kent County)
Date: Fri 7 Feb 2014
Source: Delaware Online [edited]
http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20140208/HEALTH/302080029/Whooping-cough-hits-Kent-County-Amish-community


A total of 48 people living in an Amish community in western Kent County have been infected with whooping cough, a highly contagious bacterial illness that causes violent coughing and can be fatal in infants. 80 percent of the cases are in children age 10 and younger, said Dr Karyl Rattay, director of the Delaware Division of Public Health. 25 of the cases have occurred in infants through age 6, while 15 are ages 7 to 10. The rest are older youth or adults. So far, no cases have been identified outside the Amish community. Students from at least 3 schools have fallen ill. There have been no deaths or hospitalizations, and none of those sickened is seriously ill. "It is the youngest that we are the most concerned with," she said.

In Delaware, there were 57 cases in 2012 and 29 in 2011, according to DPH's communicable diseases statistics.

Rattay said DPH held an immunization clinic in the Amish community this past week with vaccinations available. The community has been supportive and helpful, with one of the elders opening their home as a meeting place for community education, antibiotics and vaccinations. "Because of that, we believe we're going to be able to keep this well contained. They've been helping us with the investigation and ensuring that communications are reaching individuals, so we can get treatment and vaccines to individuals in the community," Rattay said.

In 2004-2005, there was a bigger outbreak of pertussis in the Kent County Amish community, resulting in 345 identified cases, mostly among school-age children.

[Byline: Jeff Montgomery, Kelly Bothum]

